1
00:00:00,420 --> 00:00:05,819
So today I’ll share with you a complete
smart money trading plan to filter and find

2
00:00:05,819 --> 00:00:09,300
the best possible trades, with the highest
probabilities.

3
00:00:09,300 --> 00:00:14,510
The trading plan revolves around supply and
demand areas, or order block, whatever you

4
00:00:14,510 --> 00:00:20,930
want to call them, fair value gaps, liquidity
runs, and one of my most reliable filters,

5
00:00:20,930 --> 00:00:22,400
pivot points.

6
00:00:22,400 --> 00:00:27,760
If you follow this approach you will achieve
remarkably precise entries, with minimal stop

7
00:00:27,760 --> 00:00:32,149
losses while targeting substantial rewards.

8
00:00:32,149 --> 00:00:37,290
So let’s begin by talking about the core
component of our trading plan, namely supply

9
00:00:37,290 --> 00:00:40,320
and demand zones, or order blocks.

10
00:00:40,320 --> 00:00:45,880
So smart money use algorithms to enter the
market strategically at important levels,

11
00:00:45,880 --> 00:00:50,410
which we, retail traders, refer to as supply
and demand.

12
00:00:50,410 --> 00:00:55,129
Instead of placing large amounts of money
all at once, they split their orders into

13
00:00:55,129 --> 00:00:59,590
smaller parts, forming tight consolidations
on the chart.

14
00:00:59,590 --> 00:01:03,600
These consolidations often precede strong
price movements.

15
00:01:03,600 --> 00:01:08,290
This technique leaves a distinct pattern on
the chart, showing where institutional money

16
00:01:08,290 --> 00:01:10,680
has been active.

17
00:01:10,680 --> 00:01:15,680
So I’ve researched a lot about institutional
trading in the past year, and from several

18
00:01:15,680 --> 00:01:19,909
sources I’ve read that smart money trade
with no protective stop loss.

19
00:01:19,909 --> 00:01:24,060
And at first, this seemed quite controversial
to me.

20
00:01:24,060 --> 00:01:29,299
I might be wrong here, but from what I’ve
read, institutions employ a strategy called

21
00:01:29,299 --> 00:01:34,950
hedging, where they simultaneously buy and
sell, to balance their positions.

22
00:01:34,950 --> 00:01:39,420
You might wonder why they do this instead
of using stop losses.

23
00:01:39,420 --> 00:01:44,659
The reason is simple: institutions have the
power to influence the market and minimize

24
00:01:44,659 --> 00:01:46,729
losses.

25
00:01:46,729 --> 00:01:51,469
Imagine they take both a short and a long
position at a key level.

26
00:01:51,469 --> 00:01:57,980
If market momentum favors the long position,
the short position faces a temporary loss.

27
00:01:57,980 --> 00:02:04,010
After the long position reaches its target,
price must then retrace back down to the short

28
00:02:04,010 --> 00:02:08,140
positions point of origin, to mitigate the
unrealized loss.

29
00:02:08,140 --> 00:02:13,140
You often hear the word mitigation in the
smart money communities.

30
00:02:13,140 --> 00:02:18,720
Mitigation is basically the point where smart
money breaks even on a losing position.

31
00:02:18,720 --> 00:02:25,470
Once the loss is mitigated, the price tends
to align with the dominant trend's momentum.

32
00:02:25,470 --> 00:02:31,760
And while smart money undergo their mitigation,
retail traders often get caught in analyzing

33
00:02:31,760 --> 00:02:38,010
double tops, flags, or various indicators
that that have nothing to do with WHY price

34
00:02:38,010 --> 00:02:40,280
does what it does.

35
00:02:40,280 --> 00:02:46,220
This allows institutional money to manipulate
retail traders' positions, by triggering "stop

36
00:02:46,220 --> 00:02:49,810
hunts" or "fake-outs" to liquidate these positions.

37
00:02:49,810 --> 00:02:55,310
In reality, these are actions executed by
institutional algorithms as part of their

38
00:02:55,310 --> 00:02:58,830
predetermined strategies.

39
00:02:58,830 --> 00:03:04,659
Now that you understand how price is moved
by smart money between areas of interest,

40
00:03:04,659 --> 00:03:08,260
let me reveal the main rules of our trading
plan.

41
00:03:08,260 --> 00:03:09,260
1.

42
00:03:09,260 --> 00:03:14,459
The supply/demand zone must cause a break
of structure or a change of character

43
00:03:14,459 --> 00:03:16,069
2.

44
00:03:16,069 --> 00:03:20,520
There must be a FVG right after the supply
or demand area

45
00:03:20,520 --> 00:03:22,159
3.

46
00:03:22,159 --> 00:03:27,610
A pivot point must offer additional confluence
– we’ll talk later about their importance

47
00:03:27,610 --> 00:03:28,610
4.

48
00:03:28,610 --> 00:03:34,680
And, a liquidity run must trap traders on
the opposite side of your trade (this one

49
00:03:34,680 --> 00:03:40,250
is optional, but if you can find it, it increases
the chances in your favor)

50
00:03:40,250 --> 00:03:47,840
So, the first step is to find a high probability
supply or demand area, meaning that area must

51
00:03:47,840 --> 00:03:51,670
cause a break of structure or a change of
character.

52
00:03:51,670 --> 00:03:57,980
You can easily spot these zones because they
appear as compact consolidation areas situated

53
00:03:57,980 --> 00:04:01,439
between strong and sudden price movements.

54
00:04:01,439 --> 00:04:06,709
You can narrow down your zone to the last
candle that moved in the opposite direction

55
00:04:06,709 --> 00:04:09,829
just before the sudden strong movement.

56
00:04:09,829 --> 00:04:15,090
In this case, when there's a bullish trend
and you want to make buy trades, you should

57
00:04:15,090 --> 00:04:20,450
pinpoint the final bearish candle before the
bullish surge.

58
00:04:20,450 --> 00:04:26,150
If the nearby candles and wicks are small,
it's better to incorporate them into the demand

59
00:04:26,150 --> 00:04:28,750
zone as well.

60
00:04:28,750 --> 00:04:35,340
So remember: this is the last area of institutional
activity prior to the impulse.

61
00:04:35,340 --> 00:04:41,970
This is the area where a hedge position may
be mitigated before continuing bullish momentum.

62
00:04:41,970 --> 00:04:45,850
The same for a supply zone, or a bearish order
block.

63
00:04:45,850 --> 00:04:51,130
You mark the final bullish candle before the
bearish down move.

64
00:04:51,130 --> 00:04:57,220
Now very important, this supply or demand
zone must be responsible for a break of structure

65
00:04:57,220 --> 00:04:59,729
(BOS) or a change of character.

66
00:04:59,729 --> 00:05:06,949
These are price shifts above or below previous
swing highs or lows, leading to trend changes

67
00:05:06,949 --> 00:05:08,320
or continuations.

68
00:05:08,320 --> 00:05:15,800
A BOS is simply a break above a previous higher
high in an uptrend, or a break below a lower

69
00:05:15,800 --> 00:05:17,950
low in a downtrend.

70
00:05:17,950 --> 00:05:24,990
The second component is a fair value gap FVG
right after the supply or demand area.

71
00:05:24,990 --> 00:05:28,640
This can greatly enhance the strength of your
trades.

72
00:05:28,640 --> 00:05:35,139
One of the primary factors you must seek when
spotting a supply or demand area is an imbalance.

73
00:05:35,139 --> 00:05:40,740
This occurs when an order block generates
such strong trading volume in the market that

74
00:05:40,740 --> 00:05:46,500
it disrupts the balance between buyers and
sellers, resulting in a gap.

75
00:05:46,500 --> 00:05:50,889
This is called an imbalance or inefficient
price action.

76
00:05:50,889 --> 00:05:56,580
These gaps act like a magnet for the price
to retreat to, aiming to correct the disruption

77
00:05:56,580 --> 00:05:58,460
in market balance.

78
00:05:58,460 --> 00:06:04,300
For a fair value gap to form, there should
be a sequence of three candles showing significant

79
00:06:04,300 --> 00:06:08,830
buying or selling, ideally in the same direction.

80
00:06:08,830 --> 00:06:14,539
When there's a substantial price movement
either up or down, a gap emerges between the

81
00:06:14,539 --> 00:06:19,010
wick of the first candle and the wick of the
last candle.

82
00:06:19,010 --> 00:06:21,610
Now, very important.

83
00:06:21,610 --> 00:06:25,120
We're not directly trading the imbalance zone
itself.

84
00:06:25,120 --> 00:06:27,860
This is one of the most common mistakes.

85
00:06:27,860 --> 00:06:32,560
If you would trade all the fair value gaps
you see on the chart, you’ll end up with

86
00:06:32,560 --> 00:06:34,040
50 trades in a single day.

87
00:06:34,040 --> 00:06:41,220
The key is to use fair value gaps to enhance
your decision-making process, but only when

88
00:06:41,220 --> 00:06:44,389
aiming for a supply or demand entry.

89
00:06:44,389 --> 00:06:49,960
A supply or demand area that triggered such
a significant disruption in price becomes

90
00:06:49,960 --> 00:06:52,430
a more reliable entry point.

91
00:06:52,430 --> 00:06:56,410
cv
Regarding this imbalance or inefficiency zone,

92
00:06:56,410 --> 00:07:02,280
it's uncertain when they will be filled, but
history shows they eventually do get filled

93
00:07:02,280 --> 00:07:04,889
when conditions are favorable.

94
00:07:04,889 --> 00:07:09,190
This is precisely why you don't solely rely
on them for trading.

95
00:07:09,190 --> 00:07:16,000
Instead, you consider them a valuable confluence
tool to have in your toolkit while analyzing

96
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,400
a market.

97
00:07:18,400 --> 00:07:21,400
The third condition is a pivot point confluence.

98
00:07:21,400 --> 00:07:27,479
These are price levels used by institutional
traders as significant levels in the market.

99
00:07:27,479 --> 00:07:32,550
These levels are calculated as an average
of prices from the performance of a market

100
00:07:32,550 --> 00:07:35,080
in the prior trading period.

101
00:07:35,080 --> 00:07:43,199
As price gets into a pivot point area, whether
it’s the pivot or an s1 or r1 level, it

102
00:07:43,199 --> 00:07:49,010
will act as a support/resistance based on
where the price has come from.

103
00:07:49,010 --> 00:07:54,560
Meaning that if the price comes from beneath
one of the levels it will be held as a resistance

104
00:07:54,560 --> 00:07:55,770
point.

105
00:07:55,770 --> 00:07:57,259
Not a guarantee, however.

106
00:07:57,259 --> 00:08:01,460
But, you are expecting to see a stall at that
level.

107
00:08:01,460 --> 00:08:07,759
If the price comes into one of those levels
from above, then you expect to see the pivot

108
00:08:07,759 --> 00:08:10,430
area act as support.

109
00:08:10,430 --> 00:08:15,520
Remember it’s not enough to find a pivot
point, and think “this is support or this

110
00:08:15,520 --> 00:08:19,110
is resistance”, so let me get long or short.

111
00:08:19,110 --> 00:08:26,720
You want to find a key pivot next to a supply
or demand zone, next to a fair value gap.

112
00:08:26,720 --> 00:08:31,979
I know ICT traders don’t use pivots, but
I consider them one of the best confirmation

113
00:08:31,979 --> 00:08:36,060
tools you could have on your charts.

114
00:08:36,060 --> 00:08:41,880
Fourth and final condition: a liquidity run
must trap traders on the opposite side of

115
00:08:41,880 --> 00:08:43,690
your possible trade.

116
00:08:43,690 --> 00:08:49,460
So if you find a demand area, leading to a
break of structure, a fair value gap next

117
00:08:49,460 --> 00:08:56,050
to it, and a pivot point around the same area,
if you find some sort of liquidity run, you’re

118
00:08:56,050 --> 00:08:59,839
in a strong position to open a buy trade.

119
00:08:59,839 --> 00:09:04,320
Market liquidity is an overlooked topic when
it comes to trading.

120
00:09:04,320 --> 00:09:08,980
Every time you open a trade you are adding
liquidity into the market.

121
00:09:08,980 --> 00:09:13,740
And you're probably familiar with the terms
"stop hunts" or "fake-outs."

122
00:09:13,740 --> 00:09:18,680
These terms describe a situation where a trader's
stop loss is triggered.

123
00:09:18,680 --> 00:09:25,790
And shortly after this loss, the price moves
in the direction the trader initially anticipated.

124
00:09:25,790 --> 00:09:31,649
This inexplicable situation arises because
institutional investors need liquidity in

125
00:09:31,649 --> 00:09:35,340
the market to execute their significant trades.

126
00:09:35,340 --> 00:09:41,120
These movements are the primary reason why
traditional retail trading methods, like relying

127
00:09:41,120 --> 00:09:47,390
on trend lines and chart patterns, like flags
and wedges, tend to be less effective.

128
00:09:47,390 --> 00:09:53,650
If a large percentage of retail traders are
using these methods, and place their stops

129
00:09:53,650 --> 00:09:59,570
around the same obvious levels, it's only
logical that institutional algorithms would

130
00:09:59,570 --> 00:10:05,510
be programmed to exploit the stop losses clustered
around these chart patterns.

131
00:10:05,510 --> 00:10:12,310
Many times, you correctly predict the direction
in which the price will move, but just before

132
00:10:12,310 --> 00:10:18,830
the actual movement, the price intentionally
triggers both buy and sell orders to gather

133
00:10:18,830 --> 00:10:20,950
liquidity from the market.

134
00:10:20,950 --> 00:10:26,620
This process aims to clear out these orders
before the real move occurs.

135
00:10:26,620 --> 00:10:32,810
You correctly anticipated the next move, but
you somehow lost money in the process.

136
00:10:32,810 --> 00:10:41,300
So developing the ability to identify areas
where liquidity might be concentrated is crucial.

137
00:10:41,300 --> 00:10:47,100
We are looking at the 5-min time frame of
S&P, chasing a potential buy trade.

138
00:10:47,100 --> 00:10:53,240
First condition is met: a Demand Zone Causes
a Break of Structure or Change of Character

139
00:10:53,240 --> 00:10:59,950
In this example, this demand zone represents
the area where buyers are likely to step in,

140
00:10:59,950 --> 00:11:04,690
causing a potential future reversal or change
in the price's direction.

141
00:11:04,690 --> 00:11:10,300
Condition no 2: Following the demand zone,
you notice that there is a fair value gap

142
00:11:10,300 --> 00:11:11,440
on its right.

143
00:11:11,440 --> 00:11:17,240
This gap indicates a sudden shift in price
from the demand area, suggesting that buyers

144
00:11:17,240 --> 00:11:20,650
have aggressively entered the market.

145
00:11:20,650 --> 00:11:26,139
Condition no 3 is also met: A Pivot Point
Offers Additional Confluence

146
00:11:26,139 --> 00:11:32,630
You can observe that S1 pivot point aligns
with the demand zone, below the fair value

147
00:11:32,630 --> 00:11:33,630
gap.

148
00:11:33,630 --> 00:11:39,630
And this price level can act as future support,
an additional layer of confluence, reinforcing

149
00:11:39,630 --> 00:11:46,269
the potential bullish bias indicated by the
demand zone and fair value gap.

150
00:11:46,269 --> 00:11:47,269
Condition no.

151
00:11:47,269 --> 00:11:52,589
4 is also present: A Liquidity Run Traps Sellers
on the Opposite Side

152
00:11:52,589 --> 00:11:58,829
As the price moves lower towards the demand
zone and pivot point, it triggers a liquidity

153
00:11:58,829 --> 00:12:05,300
run, trapping sellers who had taken short
positions in anticipation of a downward move.

154
00:12:05,300 --> 00:12:10,750
The liquidity run results in a quick upward
spike in price, further validating the bullish

155
00:12:10,750 --> 00:12:12,110
momentum.

156
00:12:12,110 --> 00:12:18,339
As all conditions in our trading plan are
met, you place a limit order or enter directly

157
00:12:18,339 --> 00:12:20,820
at the top of the demand level.

158
00:12:20,820 --> 00:12:26,250
You place a protective stop loss slightly
below the zone and your target profit is at

159
00:12:26,250 --> 00:12:32,970
the next major supply level or at a recent
swing high, or even at a pivot point.

160
00:12:32,970 --> 00:12:37,949
This is the 5-min time frame, so the stop
loss shouldn’t be too wide, and in most

161
00:12:37,949 --> 00:12:43,630
cases, you’ll get a decent risk to reward
ratio on your trades.

162
00:12:43,630 --> 00:12:51,420
We are analyzing the 5-min time frame of USD
CAD, looking for a potential sell trade.

163
00:12:51,420 --> 00:12:58,570
Step 1: We Found A Supply Zone Which Caused
a Break of Structure or Change of Character

164
00:12:58,570 --> 00:13:03,860
This is the zone where sellers are likely
to step in, potentially leading to a reversal

165
00:13:03,860 --> 00:13:08,510
or a change in the market’s direction if
price returns to it.

166
00:13:08,510 --> 00:13:14,329
You mark the last bullish candle before the
drop, or the cluster of candlesticks where

167
00:13:14,329 --> 00:13:18,300
selling pressure has historically emerged.

168
00:13:18,300 --> 00:13:24,449
Step 2: Following the supply zone, you notice
that there is a fair value gap on the chart,

169
00:13:24,449 --> 00:13:29,880
a sudden shift in price, suggesting that sellers
are actively entering the market.

170
00:13:29,880 --> 00:13:38,310
Step 3: A Pivot Point Offers Additional Confluence
In this case, R1 pivot aligns with the supply

171
00:13:38,310 --> 00:13:40,449
zone, another resistance level.

172
00:13:40,449 --> 00:13:46,930
In this scenario, the pivot point adds an
extra layer of confluence, reinforcing the

173
00:13:46,930 --> 00:13:53,360
potential bearish bias indicated by the supply
zone and fair value gap.

174
00:13:53,360 --> 00:13:59,560
Step 4: A Liquidity Run Traps buyers on the
Opposite Side

175
00:13:59,560 --> 00:14:05,600
As the price moves higher towards the supply
zone and pivot point, it triggers a liquidity

176
00:14:05,600 --> 00:14:06,970
run.

177
00:14:06,970 --> 00:14:13,790
Price experiences an upward surge, forms a
double top, and takes the liquidity, temporarily

178
00:14:13,790 --> 00:14:19,670
trapping traders who had taken long positions
in anticipation of an upward move.

179
00:14:19,670 --> 00:14:24,610
Combined with the supply zone rejection, the
liquidity run results in a sudden decline

180
00:14:24,610 --> 00:14:28,670
in price, further validating the bearish momentum.

181
00:14:28,670 --> 00:14:34,050
As I said, you may not see the liquidity run
on every setup, but it’s a valid condition

182
00:14:34,050 --> 00:14:35,220
to have.

183
00:14:35,220 --> 00:14:38,380
You sell at the bottom of the supply level.

184
00:14:38,380 --> 00:14:44,370
You place a protective stop loss slightly
above the zone and your target profit is at

185
00:14:44,370 --> 00:14:51,839
the next major demand level or at a recent
swing low, or at a pivot point.

186
00:14:51,839 --> 00:14:54,000
Here's another short position.

187
00:14:54,000 --> 00:15:00,529
First we pinpoint a supply zone on the NAS100
chart, indicating a trend continuation and

188
00:15:00,529 --> 00:15:03,960
at the same time a break of structure.

189
00:15:03,960 --> 00:15:10,110
Right after the supply zone, you notice a
fair value gap, signaling strong selling interest

190
00:15:10,110 --> 00:15:13,120
and a significant influx of sellers.

191
00:15:13,120 --> 00:15:20,680
S1 pivot point aligns with the supply zone,
above the fair value gap, acting as an additional

192
00:15:20,680 --> 00:15:25,440
resistance level and reinforcing the bearish
bias.

193
00:15:25,440 --> 00:15:31,699
As the price goes up, it even triggers a liquidity
run, taking stops above this level.

194
00:15:31,699 --> 00:15:37,649
The sudden drop in price also trapped buyers
who were positioned for an upward move.

195
00:15:37,649 --> 00:15:43,620
Considering these elements, you can make the
decision to enter a sell trade, anticipating

196
00:15:43,620 --> 00:15:50,640
the continuation of the bearish momentum generated
by the supply zone, fair value gap, pivot

197
00:15:50,640 --> 00:15:52,769
point, and liquidity run.

198
00:15:52,769 --> 00:15:55,790
4 factors indicating the same thing.

199
00:15:55,790 --> 00:15:59,110
So you sell at the bottom of the supply level.

200
00:15:59,110 --> 00:16:04,980
You place the stop loss slightly above the
zone and you take profits as price nears the

201
00:16:04,980 --> 00:16:13,630
next major demand level on its way down, or
at a recent low, or at a pivot point.

202
00:16:13,630 --> 00:16:19,709
Here's how buy trade on Apple would unfold:
First we marked this demand zone, indicating

203
00:16:19,709 --> 00:16:22,270
a potential trend continuation.

204
00:16:22,270 --> 00:16:27,520
If we look at the past price action, we see
the market making higher highs and higher

205
00:16:27,520 --> 00:16:28,520
lows.

206
00:16:28,520 --> 00:16:32,470
We have this minor break of structure here.

207
00:16:32,470 --> 00:16:38,649
Right after the demand zone, notice this fair
value gap, indicating strong buying interest

208
00:16:38,649 --> 00:16:41,529
and an aggressive influx of buyers.

209
00:16:41,529 --> 00:16:48,440
S1 pivot point aligns with the demand zone,
acting as an additional support level and

210
00:16:48,440 --> 00:16:51,650
enhancing the bullish bias.

211
00:16:51,650 --> 00:16:57,760
In this example, we don’t have a liquidity
run, but this doesn’t invalidate the setup.

212
00:16:57,760 --> 00:17:03,390
Considering these factors, you can decide
to enter a buy trade, anticipating a continuation

213
00:17:03,390 --> 00:17:11,049
of the bullish momentum generated by the demand
zone, fair value gap and the S1 pivot point

214
00:17:11,049 --> 00:17:13,799
You buy at the top of the demand level.

215
00:17:13,799 --> 00:17:19,860
A stop loss slightly below the zone and your
target profit is at the next major supply

216
00:17:19,860 --> 00:17:26,130
level or at a recent swing high, or at a pivot
point.

217
00:17:26,130 --> 00:17:29,529
If you prefer swing trading, that’s not
a problem.

218
00:17:29,529 --> 00:17:33,260
This is USDJPY on the H4 time frame.

219
00:17:33,260 --> 00:17:37,620
The only difference is that instead of using
daily pivots, we’ll change it to weekly

220
00:17:37,620 --> 00:17:38,620
pivots.

221
00:17:38,620 --> 00:17:44,500
And you might want to reduce your lot size,
because the stops will be bigger.

222
00:17:44,500 --> 00:17:45,500
Condition no.

223
00:17:45,500 --> 00:17:49,130
1: Demand Zone causes a break in market structure.

224
00:17:49,130 --> 00:17:50,660
This one is obvious.

225
00:17:50,660 --> 00:17:55,299
We mark it, from the last bearish candle before
the up move.

226
00:17:55,299 --> 00:18:00,460
And this becomes a special spot on the chart
where the price might change direction.

227
00:18:00,460 --> 00:18:06,679
A potential "U-turn zone" where buyers might
start to take control, making the price go

228
00:18:06,679 --> 00:18:08,210
up.

229
00:18:08,210 --> 00:18:09,210
Condition no.

230
00:18:09,210 --> 00:18:12,820
2: Do we have a Fair Value Gap after the Demand
Area?

231
00:18:12,820 --> 00:18:18,289
Yes we have, right after this demand zone,
there's a gap in price.

232
00:18:18,289 --> 00:18:20,530
Even multiple fair value gaps.

233
00:18:20,530 --> 00:18:27,200
It's a sign that lots of traders suddenly
wanted to buy, which pushed the price higher.

234
00:18:27,200 --> 00:18:28,200
Condition no.

235
00:18:28,200 --> 00:18:33,120
3: Do we have a weekly Pivot Point that gives
this area an extra power

236
00:18:33,120 --> 00:18:40,980
Yes, notice that S1 pivot point is very close
to this demand zone and the fair value gap.

237
00:18:40,980 --> 00:18:43,490
That’s our extra layer of support.

238
00:18:43,490 --> 00:18:47,680
It helps the price not decrease too much.

239
00:18:47,680 --> 00:18:48,680
Condition no.

240
00:18:48,680 --> 00:18:51,710
4: Do we have trapped traders with a liquidity
run

241
00:18:51,710 --> 00:18:53,790
I believe we have.

242
00:18:53,790 --> 00:18:56,460
At this minor break of structure.

243
00:18:56,460 --> 00:18:57,940
This is a "liquidity run."

244
00:18:57,940 --> 00:19:01,679
It traps sellers who were betting on the market
to go down.

245
00:19:01,679 --> 00:19:05,549
I would take this buy trade every time I’ll
see it.

246
00:19:05,549 --> 00:19:08,120
The entry can also be adjusted.

247
00:19:08,120 --> 00:19:11,799
You can use a limit order at the top of the
demand area.

248
00:19:11,799 --> 00:19:17,210
But you can also refine it even more, by moving
on a lower time frame, and finding some sort

249
00:19:17,210 --> 00:19:19,020
of confirmation.

250
00:19:19,020 --> 00:19:22,750
Now, you will encounter losing trades.

251
00:19:22,750 --> 00:19:25,510
Even when all 4 conditions are met.

252
00:19:25,510 --> 00:19:31,700
The most important part of this trading approach
is finding the right supply or demand or order

253
00:19:31,700 --> 00:19:33,179
blocks to trade.

254
00:19:33,179 --> 00:19:38,340
To efficiently plot supply and demand zones
on your chart you need to carefully considering

255
00:19:38,340 --> 00:19:43,320
a few key variables:
First is the freshness: The strongest entry

256
00:19:43,320 --> 00:19:50,220
points occur when price retracts to a supply
or demand zone for the first time after its

257
00:19:50,220 --> 00:19:51,330
creation.

258
00:19:51,330 --> 00:19:55,890
This indicates a "fresh" zone that hasn't
been revisited yet.

259
00:19:55,890 --> 00:19:58,470
Time Spent at the zone also matters.

260
00:19:58,470 --> 00:20:05,000
Less time spent there suggests a higher degree
of supply and demand imbalance, meaning that

261
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:09,740
significant market players are actively trading
at that level.

262
00:20:09,740 --> 00:20:13,270
Distance Moved away from the level matters.

263
00:20:13,270 --> 00:20:19,159
We considered that in our analysis, by looking
from break of structure or change of character.

264
00:20:19,159 --> 00:20:25,820
Areas where the price sharply turned around
indicate high-probability levels.

265
00:20:25,820 --> 00:20:31,590
Also, try to focus on the most recent supply
and demand zones.

266
00:20:31,590 --> 00:20:35,900
This is a trade I lost, taking a buy position
on the H4 time frame.

267
00:20:35,900 --> 00:20:41,150
And I’ve lost quite a few trades before,
using the same principle, until I realized

268
00:20:41,150 --> 00:20:42,180
this.

269
00:20:42,180 --> 00:20:48,650
A lot of traders focus too much on older order
blocks, but the real power lies in newest

270
00:20:48,650 --> 00:20:49,650
levels.

271
00:20:49,650 --> 00:20:56,059
I used to believe that old supply and demand
zones are just as likely to cause price reversals

272
00:20:56,059 --> 00:20:57,490
as new ones.

273
00:20:57,490 --> 00:21:03,340
I thought that old zones work just as well
as new ones, without any difference.

274
00:21:03,340 --> 00:21:06,210
When you look at the charts, it might seem
true.

275
00:21:06,210 --> 00:21:10,500
You'll see old zones making prices reverse
quite often.

276
00:21:10,500 --> 00:21:17,100
If you check charts from weeks or months ago,
you'll find old zones that made prices turn

277
00:21:17,100 --> 00:21:18,100
around.

278
00:21:18,100 --> 00:21:22,200
But, let's think about how supply and demand
zones form.

279
00:21:22,200 --> 00:21:28,419
Banks create supply and demand zones by taking
trades or cashing in their profits.

280
00:21:28,419 --> 00:21:34,179
They lead prices back to these zones because
they haven't finished making all their trades

281
00:21:34,179 --> 00:21:36,570
or taking their profits yet.

282
00:21:36,570 --> 00:21:41,039
But here's the thing: why would they wait
for months to do this?

283
00:21:41,039 --> 00:21:46,890
If they've already made a bunch of trades
to push prices up, why not finish the rest

284
00:21:46,890 --> 00:21:49,179
of their orders sooner?

285
00:21:49,179 --> 00:21:55,419
To me, it doesn't make sense that banks would
wait so long for prices to return to a zone

286
00:21:55,419 --> 00:21:58,240
just for a few remaining trades.

287
00:21:58,240 --> 00:22:03,750
If they want to finish their trades or take
their profits, they'd bring prices back to

288
00:22:03,750 --> 00:22:05,299
a zone quickly.

289
00:22:05,299 --> 00:22:09,890
They wouldn't wait around for weeks or months;
they'd do it right away.

290
00:22:09,890 --> 00:22:15,279
So very important: the time factor is going
to have a huge impact.

291
00:22:15,279 --> 00:22:22,299
In this case the zone was created at the end
of May, and I was taking a signal in August.

292
00:22:22,299 --> 00:22:28,110
Banks already moved on, took their profits,
and I was monitoring a useless area.

293
00:22:28,110 --> 00:22:33,360
So remember: the newer a supply or demand
zone is, the higher the chance that the same

294
00:22:33,360 --> 00:22:42,320
kind of trading activity is still happening
or new traders will respond to it more actively.

295
00:22:42,320 --> 00:22:46,580
Now I want to showcase a type of trade you
will encounter quite often.

296
00:22:46,580 --> 00:22:49,830
We’re looking at the H4 time frame of EURJPY.

297
00:22:49,830 --> 00:22:58,340
Step 1: A Supply Zone Leads to Change of character
This becomes our value area where the price

298
00:22:58,340 --> 00:23:04,920
might change its direction, where sellers
took control and made the price go down.

299
00:23:04,920 --> 00:23:09,770
Right after this supply zone, we spot a fair
value gap in the price.

300
00:23:09,770 --> 00:23:15,460
A sign that lots of people suddenly wanted
to sell, pushing the price lower.

301
00:23:15,460 --> 00:23:22,240
We also see that R1 pivot point is located
close to this supply zone, above the fair

302
00:23:22,240 --> 00:23:23,760
value gap.

303
00:23:23,760 --> 00:23:28,200
This is our resistance level that could stop
the price from going up.

304
00:23:28,200 --> 00:23:33,230
I don’t see a liquidity run, trapping buyers,
so this isn’t an A+ setup.

305
00:23:33,230 --> 00:23:34,740
Now here’s the thing.

306
00:23:34,740 --> 00:23:40,230
If you placed the sell order at the bottom
of the supply zone, and the stop loss above

307
00:23:40,230 --> 00:23:43,600
it, you would have probably lost the trade.

308
00:23:43,600 --> 00:23:49,350
This will happen a lot, because we are dealing
with leading signals, we are trying to anticipate

309
00:23:49,350 --> 00:23:51,230
future price movements.

310
00:23:51,230 --> 00:23:53,690
And this comes with such risk.

311
00:23:53,690 --> 00:23:59,409
If you don’t like to set limit orders around
order blocks, being on a higher time frame,

312
00:23:59,409 --> 00:24:06,070
you could move to a lower time frame, maybe
the M15 chart, and wait for a confirmation.

313
00:24:06,070 --> 00:24:11,770
Maybe a change of character to the downside,
maybe you find another fair value gap to initiate

314
00:24:11,770 --> 00:24:18,340
a short position, you wait for a VWAP breakout
to the downside, or even something else.

315
00:24:18,340 --> 00:24:23,480
With this lower time frame confirmation approach,
you would have avoided the loss.

316
00:24:23,480 --> 00:24:29,240
But don’t get too obsessed with eliminating
losses, if you’re risk management is on

317
00:24:29,240 --> 00:24:42,140
point, there’s nothing to worry about in
the long term.

